To reveal the sodium storage mechanism during the charge–discharge process, we characterized the M-FeS@C1.0 sample by ex situ XRD and TEM (Fig. 5
                        ). The XRD patterns displayed in Fig. S23 show a reduced peak intensity in the discharged (0.01 V) and charged (3 V) state compared with that of the pristine state. When discharged to 0.01 V, the strong (001) diffraction peaks of crystalline M-FeS disappeared, and a peak of Na2S at ∼ 38° was observed, with no trace of Fe peak. The peak at ∼ 38° was attributed to the formation of low-crystalline Na2S, which was also observed in XPS spectra (Fig. S24); Fe particles were assumed to be present but not evident from the XRD because of their nanoscale size [50]. After charged to 3 V, despite the disappearance of the Na2S peak, crystalline M-FeS was not formed reversibly, which is ascribed to amorphization of crystal structure, which has also been observed in other conversion-type materials [50]. High-resolution TEM images shown in Fig. 5a indicate that when M-FeS@C1.0 sample sodiated to 0.01 V, a lattice spacing of 0.21 nm was observed, corresponding to the (100) plane of Fe, which indicates the formation of Fe nanoparticles. These nanoparticles were well dispersed in the S-rich domain in the corresponding EELS maps, which would be assigned to the Fe nanoparticles being embedded in an amorphous Na2S matrix [92]. When M-FeS@C1.0 was desodiated to 3 V, the lattice spacing of 0.25 and 0.5 nm and a fast Fourier transform (FFT) pattern showing a tetragonal structure were observed; these spacings correspond to the (110) and (001) planes of M-FeS, respectively (Fig. 5b). Also, the HR-TEM images match the corresponding EELS maps of Fe and S. These results indicate that M-FeS was formed after a reversible conversion reaction. In addition to M-FeS with a tetragonal structure, some cubic and orthorhombic structures were also observed. This result is consistent with previous reports that observed a mixture of various iron sulfide phases after the conversion reaction [18,93]. The structural evolutions of M-FeS and M-FeS@C during the charge–discharge process are schematically shown in Scheme 1
